## Vercel Web Analytics Integration

Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics for the Q-Insight Next.js project.

### Changes Made

**Modified Files:**

1. **app/layout.tsx**
   - Added import statement: `import { Analytics } from "@vercel/analytics/next"`
   - Integrated `<Analytics />` component at the end of the body tag in RootLayout
   - Follows the official Next.js App Router pattern from Vercel documentation
   - Preserved existing code structure including suppressHydrationWarning attributes

2. **package.json**
   - Added `@vercel/analytics` version ^2.0.1 to dependencies

3. **package-lock.json**
   - Updated with 424 new packages to support @vercel/analytics and its dependencies
   - All dependencies installed without vulnerabilities

4. **next-env.d.ts**
   - Auto-generated type reference update (normal Next.js behavior)

### Implementation Details

- Fetched the latest installation instructions from https://vercel.com/docs/analytics/quickstart
- Identified the project as Next.js with App Router (TypeScript)
- Used npm as the package manager (consistent with existing package-lock.json)
- Followed framework-specific instructions for Next.js App Router
- Analytics component placed within the HTML body as per official documentation

### Verification

- ✅ Package installation completed successfully with no vulnerabilities
- ✅ Build process completed without errors
- ✅ TypeScript compilation passed
- ✅ Static page generation successful (3/3 pages)

### Next Steps

To start collecting analytics data:
1. Deploy the application to Vercel
2. Enable Web Analytics in the Vercel dashboard (Analytics section)
3. Data collection will begin automatically upon user visits

The Analytics component will track page views and web vitals without requiring additional configuration.
